&gt; But when I execute it, it just stuck at the cmd.ExecuteNonQuery() 

Yes, because it&#39;s still running the `DELETE FROM...` statement.

Running a `DELETE FROM...` statement is expensive!

However, as your `DELETE FROM...` statement doesn&#39;t have a predicate (there is no `WHERE` or `JOIN` criteria) it signals intent that you simply want to clear the whole table. If you want to clear a table, the best approach is to use `TRUNCATE TABLE` instead.

(Note that if you do use `TRUNCATE TABLE` you may need to disable referential and integrity constraints - these tend to be reasons that `DELETE FROM...` is slow too).

Oracle has documentation about `TRUNCATE TABLE` available: https://docs.oracle.com/cd/B28359_01/server.111/b28286/statements_10007.htm#SQLRF01707

